WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.730
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:24.350
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Good
evening everybody.

00:00:24.350 --> 00:00:27.570
My name is David Plylar and I'm
a music specialist at the Library

00:00:27.570 --> 00:00:30.780
of Congress and I'm very
pleased to be here tonight

00:00:30.780 --> 00:00:32.920
with some special people.

00:00:32.920 --> 00:00:39.340
First we have two members of
WindSync; Jack Marquardt, clarinet,

00:00:39.340 --> 00:00:42.730
and Tracy Jacobson, bassoon.

00:00:42.730 --> 00:00:45.540
And they are going to be
speaking with us a bit

00:00:45.540 --> 00:00:50.270
about their performance and
what they're up to these days.

00:00:50.270 --> 00:00:53.670
And in particular about
the new pieces going

00:00:53.670 --> 00:00:57.610
to be premiered tonight
by composer Paul Lansky.

00:00:57.610 --> 00:01:05.000
Paul Lansky is a major, major
figure in, I don't like to say

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.360 position:56%
in electronic or computer music
because he's a major figure in music

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:12.700
in general, and so we're
very pleased to have him here

00:01:12.700 --> 00:01:17.430
because he's doing a lot, kind of
in all realms of music these days.

00:01:17.430 --> 00:01:21.080
He just recently retired
from Princeton University

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:24.010
after teaching there
for 45 years, I think.

00:01:24.010 --> 00:01:25.310
[ Inaudible Response ]

00:01:25.310 --> 00:01:27.070
[ Laughter ]

00:01:27.070 --> 00:01:32.900
And I'm also pleased to say that
his wife Hannah is here who is on,

00:01:32.900 --> 00:01:38.800 position:56%
who provided the voice for the vocal
part in Six Fantasies on a Poem

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:42.780
by Thomas Campion in 1973.

00:01:42.780 --> 00:01:44.080
Is that?

00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:45.380
[ Inaudible Response ]

00:01:45.380 --> 00:01:47.060
Sixty-eight, '78.

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:50.160 position:56%
Okay so look like I have the sources
here to be able to correct me

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:55.540
with my frequent errors, but I,
so Paul Lansky was commissioned

00:01:55.540 --> 00:01:59.130
by the Caroline Royal Just
Fund in the Library of Congress

00:01:59.130 --> 00:02:02.180
and the Chamber of Music
Society of Lincoln Center.

00:02:02.180 --> 00:02:05.160
He wrote a new piece called
the Long and Short of it.

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:08.510
So let's please welcome our guests.

00:02:08.510 --> 00:02:13.480
[ Applause ]

00:02:13.480 --> 00:02:17.080
So I thought we'd dive, we're
going to start with a focus

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:19.800
on the wind quintet because
our players need some time just

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:23.250 position:56%
to get ready just before the concert
as well, but I'm going to dive

00:02:23.250 --> 00:02:26.220
into it with wind quintet
repertoire.

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:30.400
I mean what do you have, for the
most part, is a lot of new music,

00:02:30.400 --> 00:02:32.480
new transcriptions,
things like that.

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:35.260
How do you go about kind
of building programs

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:37.510
and doing the things you do?

00:02:37.510 --> 00:02:40.220
What is it that draws
you to the ensemble?

00:02:40.220 --> 00:02:43.730
&gt;&gt; Jack Marquardt: Well with
this program in particular,

00:02:43.730 --> 00:02:46.560
we were so inspired by the fact
that the Long and Short of it,

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:49.690
the world premiere piece
tonight was inspired by one

00:02:49.690 --> 00:02:54.220 position:56%
of the seminal pieces of the wind
literature, the Mozart Gran Partita.

00:02:54.220 --> 00:03:00.560
So what we decided to do was
pick three pairs of pieces,

00:03:00.560 --> 00:03:04.080
three pieces that are
standards to the one literature;

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:08.260
Barbara Summer music, Antoine
Reicha Opus 88 number two quintet

00:03:08.260 --> 00:03:14.010 position:56%
in E flat major, and the Mozart Gran
Partita arrangement we'll be doing

00:03:14.010 --> 00:03:15.630
of the Adagio movement.

00:03:15.630 --> 00:03:18.780
And we decided to pair
each one with a piece

00:03:18.780 --> 00:03:23.170
that either inspired directly
or indirectly, in a way.

00:03:23.170 --> 00:03:27.360
So with the, obviously with
the Mozart Gran Partita,

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:30.860
there's the Paul Lansky,
the Long and Short of it.

00:03:30.860 --> 00:03:33.000
And then with the Maslanka,

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:38.480 position:56%
sorry with the Reicha we're actually
pairing, Antoine Reicha was one

00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:41.890
of the most prolific composers
and one of the earliest composers

00:03:41.890 --> 00:03:45.570
of the wind quintet in
the early 19 century.

00:03:45.570 --> 00:03:49.190
He's often kind of seen as
the same way as Haydn was

00:03:49.190 --> 00:03:51.280
to the string quartet, but
only for the wind quintet.

00:03:51.280 --> 00:03:53.660
So he's kind of the
grandfather of the wind quintet

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:56.030
and David Maslanka is one

00:03:56.030 --> 00:03:59.480
of the most prolifical writers
today for the wind quintet.

00:03:59.480 --> 00:04:01.170
So we kind of paired these two.

00:04:01.170 --> 00:04:05.880
They're going to bookend into the
program and then for Summer Music,

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:09.150
we're actually pairing it with
a piece called Winter Music

00:04:09.150 --> 00:04:11.910
by a contemporary composer
named Adam Shurnberg

00:04:11.910 --> 00:04:14.450
who lives in Los Angeles.

00:04:14.450 --> 00:04:18.020
He's in his mid-30's, so he's still
kind of young and it's a piece

00:04:18.020 --> 00:04:22.420
that he found direct inspiration
from and so that's kind

00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:25.000 position:56%
of how we put this program together.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.310
More generally we like to do
a lot of our own arrangements.

00:04:27.310 --> 00:04:30.090
So this program actually only
has one of our own arrangements,

00:04:30.090 --> 00:04:33.450
the Mozart Gran Partita,
but generally you'll find

00:04:33.450 --> 00:04:36.130
that almost 90% of our programs
are our own arrangements.

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:38.550
Not just the pieces
written for winds,

00:04:38.550 --> 00:04:41.290
but orchestra, piano,
string quartet.

00:04:41.290 --> 00:04:45.510
It really runs the gamut of
anything is possible for us to do.

00:04:45.510 --> 00:04:47.810
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Do all five of
you participate in that process

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:50.520
or is it do you kind of
switch roles every once

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:52.240
in a while, take the lead, and --

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:54.520
&gt;&gt; Tracy Jacobson: Well
Jack is our primary arranger

00:04:54.520 --> 00:04:59.560
and then once Jack has put
the arrangement on the page,

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:03.090
it's a very collaborative
process from there.

00:05:03.090 --> 00:05:08.820
Where we're taking a pencil or
a pen to the part and switching

00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:12.190 position:56%
around parts and seeing what's,
what really works best for all of us

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:15.360
and once we come up with
that then we perform it

00:05:15.360 --> 00:05:16.780
and change it all again.

00:05:16.780 --> 00:05:19.690
And that's one of the
really exciting things

00:05:19.690 --> 00:05:24.430
about our particular experience
playing in wind quintet,

00:05:24.430 --> 00:05:27.830
that we have so many
performances that we're really able

00:05:27.830 --> 00:05:32.250
to in every performance have a very
different experience with the music

00:05:32.250 --> 00:05:36.720
and be very playful
and learn new things

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:38.420
about the music every
time we play it.

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:40.610
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well that strikes
me as a very convenient scenario

00:05:40.610 --> 00:05:45.100
to be able to have that ability to
have that flexibility on the fly

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:48.540
and make those decisions
depending on where you are without,

00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:51.850
you know causing any, too much
consternation to the transcriber.

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:53.380
&gt;&gt; Tracy Jacobson:
Exactly [laughter].

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:56.630 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well maybe looking
at the new piece, the Long and Short

00:05:56.630 --> 00:05:59.780
of it, I want to ask Paul
about it, but first I want

00:05:59.780 --> 00:06:03.620
to hear what you have to say about
what you see as a relationship

00:06:03.620 --> 00:06:07.890
between that piece and
the Adagio for the Mozart

00:06:07.890 --> 00:06:11.620
or like how does it fit it,
how does the inspiration seem

00:06:11.620 --> 00:06:13.490
to trace to you?

00:06:13.490 --> 00:06:15.390
&gt;&gt; Tracy Jacobson:
Well it's very obvious,

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:21.870
even from the first few notes of
Paul's piece because even just

00:06:21.870 --> 00:06:25.170
with the tempo marking and
the way that it's written,

00:06:25.170 --> 00:06:31.620 position:56%
it looks like the Mozart and there's
a particular rhythm that's present

00:06:31.620 --> 00:06:36.090
in the Gran Partita which actually,

00:06:36.090 --> 00:06:41.210
even before we played Paul's piece
we actually played the arrangement

00:06:41.210 --> 00:06:42.510
of the Partita.

00:06:42.510 --> 00:06:43.810
So we were in that mindset

00:06:43.810 --> 00:06:47.420
when we first approached
the Long and Short of it.

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:52.330
And so when we first began, it
was this feeling of familiarity

00:06:52.330 --> 00:06:54.670
from the beginning because
we were already familiar

00:06:54.670 --> 00:06:58.380
with this same rhythm
and the melody as well.

00:06:58.380 --> 00:07:02.530
It references very directly
the melody in the Gran Partita,

00:07:02.530 --> 00:07:06.770 position:56%
but with some very key changes and
then one of the most exciting things

00:07:06.770 --> 00:07:10.780
about playing this piece is
seeing where it goes differently.

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:16.280
And to find those differences
and then with many

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:19.820
of the different movements,
they're not as directly tied

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:23.960
to that original, that original
theme and that original kind

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:26.270
of motor behind what's
going on in the melody.

00:07:26.270 --> 00:07:29.610
So there's a lot of really
interesting wind textures

00:07:29.610 --> 00:07:32.940
that are very well
written for wind quintet.

00:07:32.940 --> 00:07:38.480
I must say that a lot of, a lot of
wind quintets that we've attempted

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:42.540
to perform or attempted to play
are not necessarily written

00:07:42.540 --> 00:07:44.610
by wind players and they
don't understand the need

00:07:44.610 --> 00:07:48.400
to breathe [laughter]
and some of these things.

00:07:48.400 --> 00:07:52.900
So we really have appreciated
Paul's writing.

00:07:52.900 --> 00:07:55.740
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: I think what's so
fascinating about the inspiration

00:07:55.740 --> 00:07:57.040
from the Gran Partita is not,

00:07:57.040 --> 00:07:58.570
you know one of the
beautiful melodies with,

00:07:58.570 --> 00:08:01.900
actually from this accompanimental
figure that's so present throughout

00:08:01.900 --> 00:08:04.670 position:56%
and that's the launching point for
this whole piece and I think that is

00:08:04.670 --> 00:08:07.600
so cool that the, he's
actually taken the heart beat

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:10.940
out of the Gran Partita and kind
of injected his own voice to it.

00:08:10.940 --> 00:08:12.280
Whereas a lot of times
it's much more

00:08:12.280 --> 00:08:13.970
of a straight forward inspiration.

00:08:13.970 --> 00:08:17.400
So it's really amazing to see
that kind of, that heart beat kind

00:08:17.400 --> 00:08:20.920
of wove into this really
amazing texture of this piece.

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:25.460
Well Paul, what are your thoughts
on maybe the genesis of it?

00:08:25.460 --> 00:08:28.490
What led you to this idea as
having this be a kind of kernel

00:08:28.490 --> 00:08:30.300
for the start of a wind quintet?

00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:31.600
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: It's funny.

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:32.900 position:56%
I don't really know how it happened.

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:38.810
I know the Mozart and I love the
Mozart and the Mozart always seemed

00:08:38.810 --> 00:08:45.450
to me to epitomize
breathing in wind instruments,

00:08:45.450 --> 00:08:47.710
you know you can imagine,

00:08:47.710 --> 00:08:51.500
you can imagine string
instruments playing through them.

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:53.510
The basic rhythm goes --

00:08:53.510 --> 00:08:59.080
[ Singing Out Rhythm ]

00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:02.410
Which is a long note and a short
note and that's the genesis

00:09:02.410 --> 00:09:04.320
of the title, Long and Short of it.

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:06.030
I think it's an inspired title.

00:09:06.030 --> 00:09:08.040
[ Laughter ]

00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:12.970
And so my idea, I started
out, I can't remember

00:09:12.970 --> 00:09:14.270
where I started out in this.

00:09:14.270 --> 00:09:16.890
I usually don't write pieces
in chronological order.

00:09:16.890 --> 00:09:20.350
You know things, I think I actually
started with the first movement

00:09:20.350 --> 00:09:26.730 position:56%
or the second movement, but the idea
behind using the accompaniments sort

00:09:26.730 --> 00:09:32.980
of as the DNA of the piece, as
