00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:14.720
without truly understanding
the voices of wind instruments

00:19:14.720 --> 00:19:16.750 position:56%
and what we can do and how we shine.

00:19:16.750 --> 00:19:18.850
And so that's one of
the main things.

00:19:18.850 --> 00:19:24.000
We're always looking for new
iterations of wind quintet sounds.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:28.950 position:56%
One of the things that is, one of
the things about the wind quintet is

00:19:28.950 --> 00:19:32.990
that our repertoire compared
to the repertoire of a lot

00:19:32.990 --> 00:19:36.150
of other chamber ensembles
is quite limited.

00:19:36.150 --> 00:19:40.430
Most composers wrote one or
two pieces for wind quintet,

00:19:40.430 --> 00:19:43.480
if they wrote anything for wind
quintet and there's some composers

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:46.160
that were very prolific
for wind quintet,

00:19:46.160 --> 00:19:49.200
but those pieces are quite
similar to each other

00:19:49.200 --> 00:19:54.170
and so what we have is a relatively
limited pool of repertoire and so

00:19:54.170 --> 00:19:58.020
when we're looking for composers
that want to add to that repertoire

00:19:58.020 --> 00:19:59.640
that have added to that repertoire.

00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:02.590
We want to find new sounds and
things that are really interesting

00:20:02.590 --> 00:20:08.650 position:56%
to us and the other thing that we're
really looking for is we're looking

00:20:08.650 --> 00:20:14.290
for a composer that doesn't just
want to write a piece that's based

00:20:14.290 --> 00:20:19.330
