non-computer music fairly
recently or at least starting

00:28:11.110 --> 00:28:13.620
in the late-90's and to the 2000's,

00:28:13.620 --> 00:28:19.250
but before that you were doing
predominantly, I believe,

00:28:19.250 --> 00:28:22.490
computer music and
electronic music both synthesis

00:28:22.490 --> 00:28:27.730
and in this case taking recordings
and then putting them together.

00:28:28.850 --> 00:28:32.480
One thing I noticed about
this music in general and also

00:28:32.480 --> 00:28:37.110
with everything else I've heard
that doesn't involve the computer,

00:28:37.110 --> 00:28:43.580
computer in a major capacity, is
that you immediately get a sense

00:28:43.580 --> 00:28:46.450
of a sound world of a piece
from it, of a piece of music.

00:28:46.450 --> 00:28:48.350
You don't get this, you
don't feel like oh no,

00:28:48.350 --> 00:28:51.750
here's an electronic piece that's
going to be, you know building

00:28:51.750 --> 00:28:54.990 position:56%
for 30 minutes and I have to, you
know not that there's anything wrong

00:28:54.990 --> 00:28:57.470
with those types of
pieces, but you feel like,

00:28:57.470 --> 00:29:00.210
I feel like you build
this world very quickly

00:29:00.210 --> 00:29:04.880
and one thing I would love to hear
you speak about is that process

00:29:04.880 --> 00:29:10.990
of building that world because
you have such distinctive ways

00:29:10.990 --> 00:29:14.040
of creating the sounds that are,
it's a different type of thing

00:29:14.040 --> 00:29:17.020
to say to write a wind
quintet than it is to actually,

00:29:17.020 --> 00:29:20.780
you know create the sounds from
the ground up or collect the sounds

00:29:20.780 --> 00:29:22.950
and put them together
in a particular way.

00:29:22.950 --> 00:29:27.920
Some of them are more labor
intensive, I don't know.

00:29:27.920 --> 00:29:29.720
What is your experience with that?

00:29:29.720 --> 00:29:35.360
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Well I grew up in
the really learning to love music

00:29:35.360 --> 00:29:38.140
in the 50's and the 60's and part

00:29:38.140 --> 00:29:40.260
of what I did was just
listen to records.

00:29:40.260 --> 00:29:42.740
My father actually was a
recording engineer and he worked

00:29:42.740 --> 00:29:46.510
for Capital Records in New York
and so I spent a lot of time,

00:29:46.510 --> 00:29:50.890
you know visiting his recording
studio and so recording

00:29:50.890 --> 00:29:53.300
in general is very
interesting to me.

00:29:53.300 --> 00:29:58.650 position:56%
And I realized probably quite early
on that there, as far as Avant Garde

00:29:58.650 --> 00:30:05.740 position:56%
or experimental or electronic music,
is really a sort of a bifurcation

00:30:05.740 --> 00:30:10.030
of different kinds of
uses of loud speakers.

00:30:10.030 --> 00:30:15.160
The standard electronic model, the
loud speaker is the instrument,

00:30:15.160 --> 00:30:21.370
you know it goes crunch and
squeak and squeal and grind and,

00:30:21.370 --> 00:30:24.560
and that's sort of you
know what we come to expect

00:30:24.560 --> 00:30:28.790 position:56%
from electronic music, but one thing
that I liked a lot was the idea

00:30:28.790 --> 00:30:33.510
that loud speakers are
windows into a virtual space.

00:30:33.510 --> 00:30:35.040
Let me repeat that.

00:30:35.040 --> 00:30:36.860
Windows into a virtual space.

00:30:36.860 --> 00:30:39.200
So you know you listen
to a recording

00:30:39.200 --> 00:30:43.770
and if the recording is done
well, then this real tendency

00:30:43.770 --> 00:30:48.310
of the recording engineer
to create the illusion

00:30:48.310 --> 00:30:52.310
that something is actually
happening in the loud speakers

00:30:52.310 --> 00:30:55.040
and I got very interesting
in doing that sort of thing

00:30:55.040 --> 00:30:57.880
with electronic music and
creating the impression

00:30:57.880 --> 00:31:00.440
that there's a world beyond,

00:31:00.440 --> 00:31:04.320
behind the loud speakers
that's functioning that way.

00:31:04.320 --> 00:31:08.230
And I spent a lot of
time working with voice.

00:31:08.230 --> 00:31:14.150
I used Hannah, I'm very lucky to
have a, such a wonderful reader

00:31:14.150 --> 00:31:17.650
for my pieces and I spent
a lot of time trying

00:31:17.650 --> 00:31:20.540
to model real instruments.

00:31:20.540 --> 00:31:24.130
And to get real instruments,
to get the sound of a violin

00:31:24.130 --> 00:31:28.510
or the sound of, you
know armpit farts.

00:31:28.510 --> 00:31:31.040
[ Laughter ]

00:31:31.040 --> 00:31:35.660
And so a lot of my, most of my
pieces, actually I think almost all

00:31:35.660 --> 00:31:41.320
of my electronic pieces consist of
something that is a virtual world

00:31:41.320 --> 00:31:46.850
of its own and this became
sort of an obsession with me

00:31:46.850 --> 00:31:52.990
and then one day I thought well
rather than synthesize the violin,

00:31:52.990 --> 00:31:55.460
why not use a real violin?

00:31:55.460 --> 00:32:03.850
And I had done a lot of
things with recording players

00:32:03.850 --> 00:32:08.310
and using their sounds, but to
actually use the real violin

00:32:08.310 --> 00:32:12.550
in a way that real
violinist would appreciate.

00:32:12.550 --> 00:32:19.730
Sort of the point of the
exercise, so there's a real,

00:32:19.730 --> 00:32:22.070
I don't want to go
too far afield here,

00:32:22.070 --> 00:32:25.350
but let me just say really quickly
that there's a different kind

00:32:25.350 --> 00:32:31.100
of compositional conception
behind created and frozen

00:32:31.100 --> 00:32:35.510
in time electronic music
and music for instruments.

00:32:35.510 --> 00:32:39.520
One thing that I like a lot
of is the idea of danger

00:32:39.520 --> 00:32:41.430
in music, in performance.

00:32:41.430 --> 00:32:46.060
So when you hear somebody perform,
there's always the possibility

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:47.930
that they'll miss a
note, that they'll die

00:32:47.930 --> 00:32:51.290
of a heart attack [laughter], that,

00:32:51.290 --> 00:32:52.590
you know something
strange will happen.

00:32:52.590 --> 00:32:55.970
With electronic music, it's
always fixed and the only thing

00:32:55.970 --> 00:32:59.670
that can happen really is the
tape machine will break down,

00:32:59.670 --> 00:33:01.030
which has happened actually.

00:33:01.030 --> 00:33:03.040
[ Laughter ]

00:33:03.040 --> 00:33:04.480
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: At the same
time you have these certain times

00:33:04.480 --> 00:33:07.750
where you have referential things
like say with cars going by

00:33:07.750 --> 00:33:09.520
or something like that
where you do get the sense

00:33:09.520 --> 00:33:11.370
of potentially sense of --

00:33:11.370 --> 00:33:15.340
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Yeah so almost
all the, I think I have one piece

00:33:15.340 --> 00:33:18.700
that I did toward the end
of my time doing this,

00:33:18.700 --> 00:33:21.460
which is truly electronic.

00:33:21.460 --> 00:33:26.520
It doesn't reference real world
sounds, but all of the pieces,

00:33:26.520 --> 00:33:30.860
virtually all the pieces that
I did consist of some aspect

00:33:30.860 --> 00:33:33.300
of focusing on realities.

00:33:33.300 --> 00:33:42.400 position:56%
Some way to sort of peer into a real
world and it got, it was getting old

00:33:42.400 --> 00:33:45.700
around 2005 or 6 with
Table's Clear turned

00:33:45.700 --> 00:33:51.930 position:56%
out to be a cathartic experience and
percussionist in particular ask me

00:33:51.930 --> 00:33:57.810 position:56%
for a transcription of Table's Clear
and there's no way I can do that.

00:33:57.810 --> 00:34:00.780
I mean I used all kinds of
random number generators

00:34:00.780 --> 00:34:03.040
and different things
to create the rhythms

00:34:03.040 --> 00:34:04.670
and textures of Table's Clear.

00:34:04.670 --> 00:34:07.750
So that got me into
writing percussion music

00:34:07.750 --> 00:34:12.000 position:56%
and I've written a lot of percussion
music and it's a different world.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:17.150
You know I was basically
60 when I started sort of,

00:34:17.150 --> 00:34:18.700 position:56%
when I finished doing computer music

00:34:18.700 --> 00:34:21.260
and started doing this
stuff and it was great.

00:34:21.260 --> 00:34:26.850
It was like I was beginning
again and starting over.

00:34:26.850 --> 00:34:28.820
So it's been a really
interesting voyage.

00:34:28.820 --> 00:34:35.030
You know, my one regret is that,
well let me not go into regrets.

00:34:35.030 --> 00:34:37.040
[ Laughter ]

00:34:37.040 --> 00:34:39.380
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well it's,
there are certain things

00:34:39.380 --> 00:34:42.290
that you said that, one thing that
I would like to say about your,

00:34:42.290 --> 00:34:45.540
many of your pieces in
general is that there's

00:34:45.540 --> 00:34:48.730
that great deal of activity.

00:34:48.730 --> 00:34:52.660
There's a lot of things to say
with granular types of processes

00:34:52.660 --> 00:34:56.810
and things like that going on,
but they're so controlled both

00:34:56.810 --> 00:35:02.320
like in a tonal sense, well in
many cases a harmonic sense,

00:35:02.320 --> 00:35:07.890
but also a sense of like you find
the pitch material and the types

00:35:07.890 --> 00:35:11.630 position:56%
of things in the types of sound that
you're using and you control them

00:35:11.630 --> 00:35:14.600
so clearly even with
all this activity.

00:35:14.600 --> 00:35:19.760
So it feels like there's this
great undercurrent of energy,

00:35:19.760 --> 00:35:22.510
but you're kind of suppressing
it and kind of floating atop

00:35:22.510 --> 00:35:24.570
and I don't know if
that's just something

00:35:24.570 --> 00:35:27.200
that has always been a part of
your music or do you think of it

00:35:27.200 --> 00:35:30.200
that way at all or maybe not.

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:33.250
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Well,
it's complicated.

00:35:33.250 --> 00:35:42.390
I did a piece in 1984 called Idle
Chatter, which has gotten a lot

00:35:42.390 --> 00:35:49.000
of play and I started, I was
inspired by actually a trip,

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:53.450
driving into New York City going
through the Lincoln Tunnel coming

00:35:53.450 --> 00:35:54.900
out at the end of the
Lincoln Tunnel.

00:35:54.900 --> 00:35:58.820
Some people how lived in New York
remember the days when the mouth

00:35:58.820 --> 00:36:05.400
of the Lincoln Tunnel was really a
pretty seedy place and you came out

00:36:05.400 --> 00:36:09.110
and there was a bunch of teenagers,
[inaudible] teenagers standing

00:36:09.110 --> 00:36:12.870
around the cop, sort of bouncing
up and down and he had a smile

00:36:12.870 --> 00:36:17.550
on his face and I rolled down
the window and they were doing,

00:36:17.550 --> 00:36:21.110
you know a rap to the cop
and he was enjoying it

00:36:21.110 --> 00:36:24.010
and I thought well what
a great idea for a piece.

00:36:24.010 --> 00:36:29.180
So I went home and started to
do it and I took Hannah's voice

00:36:29.180 --> 00:36:34.620
and chopped it up into little bits
and tuned the bits and I started

00:36:34.620 --> 00:36:39.280
to do a real fancy, you know
harmonic thing with all kinds

00:36:39.280 --> 00:36:42.600
of weird chords and it just
became totally exhausting.

00:36:42.600 --> 00:36:48.380 position:56%
So I narrowed it down to an F. Every
one doing F and that time it's good,

00:36:48.380 --> 00:36:51.280
but it got a little old after
a while so I added an E flat

00:36:51.280 --> 00:36:55.730
and then I added D and B
flat and I had B flat major.

00:36:55.730 --> 00:37:00.720
And you have to realize that in
the late 70's and early 80's,

00:37:00.720 --> 00:37:05.180 position:56%
that Princeton, nobody was taken
seriously if they wrote tonal music.

00:37:05.180 --> 00:37:08.550
You know we were all
sort of experimentalists

00:37:08.550 --> 00:37:13.110
and I had done my share of fancy
ways of organizing harmony,

00:37:13.110 --> 00:37:16.230
but I realized that the
computer actually freed me

00:37:16.230 --> 00:37:20.710
up to write tonal music and
I love writing tonal music.

00:37:20.710 --> 00:37:22.010
I love tonality.

00:37:22.010 --> 00:37:26.010
I think tonality is one of
the great accomplishments

00:37:26.010 --> 00:37:34.200
of western civilization and the
piece sort of flowed in tonal terms

00:37:34.200 --> 00:37:39.350
and since then, most of my pieces
are in way or another diatonic.

00:37:39.350 --> 00:37:44.270
I don't, the piece tonight
is very explicitly diatonic.

00:37:44.270 --> 00:37:46.770
I do other pieces which
are more or less diatonic

00:37:46.770 --> 00:37:50.620
and so the electronic sort
of freed me, in a way.

00:37:50.620 --> 00:37:58.800 position:56%
So I still got respect, but I could,
I can do things with tonality.

00:37:58.800 --> 00:38:00.210
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well
one, one other thing

00:38:00.210 --> 00:38:02.850
that I have always been
curious about, I think people

00:38:02.850 --> 00:38:06.760
who haven't tried to produce
their own electronic music,

00:38:06.760 --> 00:38:11.220
especially back when, you know
you had to rent time at a computer

00:38:11.220 --> 00:38:14.220
if you were going to
or you know just be

00:38:14.220 --> 00:38:15.520
on the [speaking over one another].

00:38:15.520 --> 00:38:16.820
Really, oh wow.

00:38:16.820 --> 00:38:18.840
That was at university.

00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:20.850
So back in the day when
it was really you had

00:38:20.850 --> 00:38:24.290
to invest a great deal of time
to get any sort of feedback

00:38:24.290 --> 00:38:27.900
versus today when you have a
bit more of immediate feedback,

00:38:27.900 --> 00:38:32.300
but not necessarily mastery
of say if somebody were just

00:38:32.300 --> 00:38:33.880
to go and look at software.

00:38:33.880 --> 00:38:35.240
They would have some
immediate feedback,

00:38:35.240 --> 00:38:37.640
but they wouldn't still
have mastery of that,

00:38:37.640 --> 00:38:40.450
how to produce exactly
what they want to produce.

00:38:40.450 --> 00:38:44.860
How does that compare what you were
doing in those days versus the way

00:38:44.860 --> 00:38:46.460
that you approach composition now?

00:38:46.460 --> 00:38:50.030
Do you, are you thankful
that you have like,

00:38:50.030 --> 00:38:56.200
that you're a bit divorced from
those technological impediments

00:38:56.200 --> 00:39:00.040
or was that something that
helped the compositional process?

00:39:00.040 --> 00:39:03.360
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Well I loved
getting under the hood.

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:05.620
I actually wrote a lot of software.

00:39:05.620 --> 00:39:11.710
I discovered strangely that I
had a knack for writing software

00:39:11.710 --> 00:39:15.000
and I did a lot of it, but I
always did it in the service

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:16.810
of a piece in one way or another.

00:39:16.810 --> 00:39:18.980
So what was your question?

00:39:18.980 --> 00:39:21.710
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: So the amount
of time that you would take just

00:39:21.710 --> 00:39:25.730
to be able to get to where you, and
then utilize that software or --

00:39:25.730 --> 00:39:28.200 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Oh it was very slow.

00:39:28.200 --> 00:39:32.610
I typically spend the
year on a piece

00:39:32.610 --> 00:39:38.150
and you mentioned the Six Fantasies
on a Poem by Thomas Campion,

00:39:38.150 --> 00:39:39.990
which I did in the late 70's.

00:39:39.990 --> 00:39:44.260
It took me a year and a half and
it was a very tedious process.

00:39:44.260 --> 00:39:47.910
For that piece I can actually
work at home with the line

00:39:47.910 --> 00:39:54.620
at a time monitor, 30
characters a second,

00:39:54.620 --> 00:39:59.190
which just was transmitting code
and then I'd have to go into school

00:39:59.190 --> 00:40:04.690
and sign out a digital tape and
take the digital tape into a lab,

00:40:04.690 --> 00:40:08.050
which had mini computers.

00:40:08.050 --> 00:40:12.060
We used Hewlett Packard's very
first computer and there was noise

00:40:12.060 --> 00:40:14.800
and whirling and it was
called the D Day converter

00:40:14.800 --> 00:40:18.680
and I remember picking my son Jonah
up from nursery school one day

00:40:18.680 --> 00:40:22.040
and I said he had a friend I had
to take home too and I said we have

00:40:22.040 --> 00:40:27.200
to go to the D Day converter and
Jonah said he was I guess five

00:40:27.200 --> 00:40:33.510
at the time, maybe six, said have
you ever been to a D Day converter?

00:40:33.510 --> 00:40:36.150
[ Laughter ]

00:40:36.150 --> 00:40:39.470
And I often wondered what
his consciousness was

00:40:39.470 --> 00:40:43.950
like because he would go and hear
his mother's voice trans modified

00:40:43.950 --> 00:40:46.380
over a loud speaker.

00:40:46.380 --> 00:40:51.690
So the process was fun and I
had patience for it and I seemed

00:40:51.690 --> 00:40:56.800
to get a lot of music out of
it, but it's almost the case

00:40:56.800 --> 00:40:59.960
that these days when
it's so easy to do.

00:40:59.960 --> 00:41:03.260
That, you know the sort
of fun is taken out of it.

00:41:03.260 --> 00:41:05.270
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well I think in
some cases it might be easy to get

00:41:05.270 --> 00:41:08.760
that start, but it's harder
to sometimes hear that mastery

00:41:08.760 --> 00:41:12.660
that you're presenting in all
these pieces over the years.

00:41:13.710 --> 00:41:15.650
With new projects that
you're up to you mentioned

00:41:15.650 --> 00:41:17.980
that you're doing some
more percussion music?

00:41:17.980 --> 00:41:21.040
I know that [inaudible] percussion,
you did a quartet for them.

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:25.250 position:56%
Do you have anything else coming up?

00:41:25.250 --> 00:41:29.540
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: I just heard
a song for guitar and voice

00:41:29.540 --> 00:41:35.960
about insomnia [laughter] and
the song is, I wrote the words,

00:41:35.960 --> 00:41:37.940
the song is called Just Once

00:41:37.940 --> 00:41:41.330
and the insomniac says
just once let me sleep

00:41:41.330 --> 00:41:43.550
through the night [laughter].

00:41:43.550 --> 00:41:44.850
So --

00:41:44.850 --> 00:41:47.660
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Is that
for David Stirbin also --

00:41:47.660 --> 00:41:50.980
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: No, it's for Bill
Anderson who composes [inaudible]

00:41:50.980 --> 00:41:56.100
for New Jersey and yeah I have
a bunch of other pieces in the,

00:41:56.100 --> 00:41:58.060
but nice thing about
being retired is

00:41:58.060 --> 00:42:00.780 position:56%
that I can devote all my time to it.

00:42:00.780 --> 00:42:04.600
So it's fun.

00:42:04.600 --> 00:42:05.900
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well that's great.

00:42:05.900 --> 00:42:09.450
I think maybe we'll open it up to
ask if anybody has any questions

00:42:09.450 --> 00:42:10.750
that they want to ask you.

00:42:10.750 --> 00:42:12.520
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Yeah, please
ask me a question [laughter].

00:42:12.520 --> 00:42:15.560
I'll do what I used to do with
undergraduates, I say I'm going

00:42:15.560 --> 00:42:17.510
to hold my breath until
you ask me a question.

00:42:17.510 --> 00:42:21.040
[ Laughter ]

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:23.610
&gt;&gt; Have you worked
with, have you worked

00:42:23.610 --> 00:42:26.590 position:56%
with the Princeton Laptop Orchestra?

00:42:26.590 --> 00:42:29.700
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Yes actually
the last piece I did,

00:42:29.700 --> 00:42:32.740
electronic piece was a piece
for the Laptop Orchestra.

00:42:32.740 --> 00:42:39.170
It's called the Guy
Walks into a Modal Bar.

00:42:39.170 --> 00:42:41.550
It uses things called
modal bar synthesis.

00:42:41.550 --> 00:42:44.840
We had a guy at Princeton named
Perry Cook who was very good

00:42:44.840 --> 00:42:47.620
at doing what are called
physical models, that is instead

00:42:47.620 --> 00:42:53.040 position:56%
of modeling the way the sound works,
the way the sound sort of evolves

00:42:53.040 --> 00:43:00.520
over time like, you know you'd have
a pop and decay, it actually is,

00:43:00.520 --> 00:43:06.470
well for a flute for example,
you have the right going wave

00:43:06.470 --> 00:43:08.650
and the returning wave
and that sort of thing.

00:43:08.650 --> 00:43:14.220
So I did it with undergraduates
and we did,

00:43:14.220 --> 00:43:18.510
I must say I wasn't
thrilled with it.

00:43:18.510 --> 00:43:23.000
It's, you sort of, you know you
can do anything in real time now,

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:29.020
but this was not my,
not my favorite.

00:43:29.020 --> 00:43:30.820
Ask me another question.

00:43:30.820 --> 00:43:34.220
[ Laughter ]

00:43:34.220 --> 00:43:36.020
I'll hold my breath.

00:43:36.020 --> 00:43:39.080
[ Laughter ]

00:43:39.080 --> 00:43:40.380
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: If you wait,
I'll bring a microphone up to you.

00:43:40.380 --> 00:43:42.680
Thanks.

00:43:45.120 --> 00:43:48.160
&gt;&gt; Hi, you were talking
about tonality.

00:43:48.160 --> 00:43:51.690
You use the word diatonic,
which I'm,

00:43:51.690 --> 00:43:56.440
to be honest with you
not very familiar with.

00:43:56.440 --> 00:43:59.650
Can you explain that
a little bit more.

00:43:59.650 --> 00:44:01.950 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: What diatonic means?

00:44:01.950 --> 00:44:03.250
&gt;&gt; Yes, please.

00:44:03.250 --> 00:44:04.840
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Yeah, you
hear a whole slew of notes

00:44:04.840 --> 00:44:07.730 position:56%
and you reference them in one way or
another, if you're, you know I think

00:44:07.730 --> 00:44:10.710 position:56%
with Milton Babbitt and George
Pearl and other composers like that,

00:44:10.710 --> 00:44:14.340
they reference them as notes
of the chromatic scale.

00:44:14.340 --> 00:44:17.630
With, one thing I love
about tonality is that,

00:44:17.630 --> 00:44:22.910
or using diatonic tonality as
a model is that you hear a note

00:44:22.910 --> 00:44:24.950
and you think of it
as a scale degree.

00:44:24.950 --> 00:44:31.220 position:56%
So if I go [singing harmony] you can
think of that as, or you can think

00:44:31.220 --> 00:44:37.150
of it as the third note of a G
major scale [singing harmony].

00:44:37.150 --> 00:44:39.510
Or you can think of it as the
second note of an A major scale.

00:44:39.510 --> 00:44:44.040
[ Singing Harmony ]

00:44:44.040 --> 00:44:49.450
[Inaudible] in a performance and
when I used to teach tonal harmony

00:44:49.450 --> 00:44:51.230
to beginners, I would
take the [inaudible]

00:44:51.230 --> 00:44:53.190
and fourth piano concerto
which starts

00:44:53.190 --> 00:44:56.510
out with a G major chord
with a B on the top.

00:44:56.510 --> 00:45:02.040
[ Singing Harmony ]

00:45:02.040 --> 00:45:03.840
And then it turns into B major.

00:45:03.840 --> 00:45:08.050
[ Singing Harmony ]

00:45:08.050 --> 00:45:14.200
So you just, the ability to locate
a note as a place in a scale.

00:45:14.200 --> 00:45:18.380
So the note has a quality and a
meaning that depends a lot on,

00:45:18.380 --> 00:45:23.830
you know the tonal context and
I guess the short answer is

00:45:23.830 --> 00:45:27.170
when I think of things in diatonic
terms, I do think of things

00:45:27.170 --> 00:45:29.370
as members of a, as scale degrees.

00:45:29.370 --> 00:45:33.210
So it's, you know it's
the second scale degree

00:45:33.210 --> 00:45:34.510
or it's the first scale degree.

00:45:34.510 --> 00:45:37.640
So the note has a quality
and the wonderful thing

00:45:37.640 --> 00:45:40.370
about this is I don't want
to go too far afield here,

00:45:40.370 --> 00:45:42.950
but the wonderful thing about
this is it give you a metric

00:45:42.950 --> 00:45:44.950
for distance.

00:45:44.950 --> 00:45:50.850 position:56%
You do something in G major and it's
going to be very far from B major

00:45:50.850 --> 00:45:55.110
and the wonderful thing Beethoven
does, he jumps from G major

00:45:55.110 --> 00:45:59.080
to the B major and then sort
of wonders back to G major.

00:45:59.080 --> 00:46:03.050
So that's the kind of thing
that I'm thinking about.

00:46:03.050 --> 00:46:08.210
The, I did a lot work in the
60's on new theories of harmony.

00:46:08.210 --> 00:46:10.840
George Pearl, I collaborated
with George Pearl

00:46:10.840 --> 00:46:18.440
on a thing called 12 Tone Tonality
and it just didn't work for me.

00:46:18.440 --> 00:46:21.850
So, but it's fun.

00:46:21.850 --> 00:46:23.670
Does that make some sense?

00:46:23.670 --> 00:46:26.490
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: I know you've
written about like reference

00:46:26.490 --> 00:46:30.420
versus implication and those types
of things, but there's this element

00:46:30.420 --> 00:46:34.600
of implication that comes with
the knowledge of a system and --

00:46:34.600 --> 00:46:35.900
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Yeah.

00:46:35.900 --> 00:46:37.200
[ Speaking Over One Another ]

00:46:37.200 --> 00:46:40.320
The wonderful thing about
tonality is that you can,

00:46:40.320 --> 00:46:44.690
you can imply things
that are going to happen.

00:46:44.690 --> 00:46:49.100
You know you do something and that
sort of implies a way of thinking

00:46:49.100 --> 00:46:54.290
about things and it implies
a way of moving in time.

00:46:54.290 --> 00:46:58.570
With 12 Tone music, it doesn't
work quite the same way.

00:46:58.570 --> 00:47:00.240
That I used to differentiate

00:47:00.240 --> 00:47:03.100
between the two we called
[inaudible] combinational system,

00:47:03.100 --> 00:47:05.550
which was tonality and the
other [inaudible] system

00:47:05.550 --> 00:47:08.670
which means you're worried
about different arrangements

00:47:08.670 --> 00:47:12.670
of the same set of objects and
that probably confuses you more

00:47:12.670 --> 00:47:13.970
than anything.

00:47:13.970 --> 00:47:15.660
[ Laughter ]

00:47:15.660 --> 00:47:18.590
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: I think
we had another question.

00:47:18.590 --> 00:47:20.250
&gt;&gt; Yeah, you know one thing

00:47:20.250 --> 00:47:24.780
about composing electronic
computer music is

00:47:24.780 --> 00:47:29.250
that you don't need a performer,
at least not a living performer

00:47:29.250 --> 00:47:34.300
and then you go back to composing
music that required performance.

00:47:34.300 --> 00:47:37.650
I'm just wondering how you
felt about suddenly having

00:47:37.650 --> 00:47:41.520
to have performers
involved in your work?

00:47:41.520 --> 00:47:43.910
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Well that
actually became the focus

00:47:43.910 --> 00:47:47.290
of my intention especially
with percussion music.

00:47:47.290 --> 00:47:50.290
When I started to write
percussion music,

00:47:50.290 --> 00:47:53.740
I guess my first really percussion
piece was a piece called Threads,

00:47:53.740 --> 00:47:56.050
which I did in 2005.

00:47:56.050 --> 00:47:59.890
When I first started to do
percussion music, it was very much

00:47:59.890 --> 00:48:03.130
like doing electronic music.

00:48:03.130 --> 00:48:07.210
I'm worrying about envelope and I'd
worry about attack and decay and so

00:48:07.210 --> 00:48:11.020
that felt great, but at a
certain point I lost the thread,

00:48:11.020 --> 00:48:17.690
pardon the pun, and it started to
get mysterious and then I realized

00:48:17.690 --> 00:48:22.820
that one of my roles as a
composer was to be a choreographer

00:48:22.820 --> 00:48:27.680
and with percussionist, that's
really the name of the game.

00:48:27.680 --> 00:48:31.430
You know, I imagine them
moving in various kinds

00:48:31.430 --> 00:48:34.770
of synchronic ways
and, is that a word?

00:48:34.770 --> 00:48:36.070
Synchronic?

00:48:36.070 --> 00:48:38.460
Well it is now.

00:48:38.460 --> 00:48:42.380
I imagine them moving in
various ways and you know

00:48:42.380 --> 00:48:46.100
like with greased chests
and big drums

00:48:46.100 --> 00:48:51.790 position:56%
and when you see a percussion
group, there are some percussionists

00:48:51.790 --> 00:48:55.450
who are like dancers
and so the notion

00:48:55.450 --> 00:49:01.040 position:56%
of being a choreographer became part
of the, part of the whole action.

00:49:01.040 --> 00:49:04.580 position:56%
I liked that a lot, so I'm actually,

00:49:04.580 --> 00:49:07.770
a lot of my electronic
music had been danced to,

00:49:07.770 --> 00:49:09.710
but I would never persuaded by it.

00:49:09.710 --> 00:49:13.350
But looking at, you know
a percussion ensemble

00:49:13.350 --> 00:49:18.650
as a dance troop really makes
it seem quite different.

00:49:21.040 --> 00:49:23.660
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Just to follow up
on that, you had mentioned earlier

00:49:23.660 --> 00:49:28.030 position:56%
that a lot of the work you were
doing in electronic music was trying

00:49:28.030 --> 00:49:31.460
to get towards a more realistic
sound like something that was

00:49:31.460 --> 00:49:35.500
in the real world, but
that was created by you.

00:49:36.610 --> 00:49:38.100
Is there any flip of that?

00:49:38.100 --> 00:49:42.650
Do you find with non-electronic
music that you're writing,

00:49:42.650 --> 00:49:46.950
do you find yourself moving back in
some way towards a different type

00:49:46.950 --> 00:49:49.510
of ideal idiom or something
like that?

00:49:49.510 --> 00:49:51.560
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Well
it's really different.

00:49:51.560 --> 00:49:55.750
One thing that I have to admit is

00:49:55.750 --> 00:50:00.120
that when I was doing electronic
music, it was before the days

00:50:00.120 --> 00:50:03.670
of computer programs that
could write your score for you

00:50:03.670 --> 00:50:08.700
and I remember writing a,
spending six months writing a piece

00:50:08.700 --> 00:50:12.810
and spending a year writing
the parts and then hearing it

00:50:12.810 --> 00:50:15.350
and wishing I could revise it.

00:50:15.350 --> 00:50:18.400
So the great thing
about these programs is

00:50:18.400 --> 00:50:25.920
that it makes revision possible
and my publisher is very graceful

00:50:25.920 --> 00:50:30.040
about it and doesn't make too much
of fuss when I say please throw

00:50:30.040 --> 00:50:31.340
out the score I just sent you.

00:50:31.340 --> 00:50:33.040
[ Laughter ]

00:50:33.040 --> 00:50:34.840
I've got the revised
version and I'm going

00:50:34.840 --> 00:50:37.250
to probably revise
tonight's piece in some way.

00:50:37.250 --> 00:50:40.010
So if anyone has any great
suggestions for ways to revise it.

00:50:40.010 --> 00:50:41.310
[ Laughter ]

00:50:41.310 --> 00:50:43.910
Please let me know.

00:50:43.910 --> 00:50:46.240
Also one thing that
it makes possible,

00:50:46.240 --> 00:50:49.090
which I like a lot is
it makes it possible

00:50:49.090 --> 00:50:53.390
to compose and out of order.

00:50:53.390 --> 00:50:55.700
So you know you write
something and then you say well,

00:50:55.700 --> 00:50:59.060
in the middle of that there
should be this, something longer,

00:50:59.060 --> 00:51:01.410
and actually the beginning
should be different

00:51:01.410 --> 00:51:03.410
or there should be an
additional part of the beginning.

00:51:03.410 --> 00:51:10.520
So I don't compose in, things
in time the ordered ways.

00:51:10.520 --> 00:51:13.560
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Well as
before you would be forced

00:51:13.560 --> 00:51:16.560
to put together the
program, compile it,

00:51:16.560 --> 00:51:19.730
and go through that before
you get any feedback?

00:51:19.730 --> 00:51:21.120 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: It's very different.

00:51:21.120 --> 00:51:25.250
It's very different and I'm
very glad that I did it.

00:51:25.250 --> 00:51:27.850
You know I loved writing
electronic music.

00:51:27.850 --> 00:51:31.950
It was great, you know I'd go
up to my studio after breakfast,

00:51:31.950 --> 00:51:38.280
in my bathrobe, and I'd just
play with sound and it was great

00:51:38.280 --> 00:51:41.080
and now I can play with
sound to a certain extent,

00:51:41.080 --> 00:51:43.630
except you know the many
realizations as you do it,

00:51:43.630 --> 00:51:47.150
you're pieces always sound
so dreadful that you have

00:51:47.150 --> 00:51:49.320
to know what you're doing.

00:51:49.320 --> 00:51:55.130
But it's very different and I love
this, one thing I really liked

00:51:55.130 --> 00:52:00.230
about doing electronic music was
the feeling of being in a studio,

00:52:00.230 --> 00:52:06.340
a pottery studio or a, you
know any kind of studio

00:52:06.340 --> 00:52:11.780
where you fabricate something and
I'm a great admirer of composers

00:52:11.780 --> 00:52:15.670
who can just sort of write a piece
out and, with a pencil and paper.

00:52:15.670 --> 00:52:20.870
Which I don't do, but I love the,
you know the feeling of being

00:52:20.870 --> 00:52:23.880
in a workshop type environment .

00:52:23.880 --> 00:52:25.180
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Even
though you're a [inaudible],

00:52:25.180 --> 00:52:28.560
it seems like a performative
act to be doing all of that.

00:52:28.560 --> 00:52:29.860
I don't know, that's to me --

00:52:29.860 --> 00:52:31.160
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: Yeah I know.

00:52:31.160 --> 00:52:32.910
It's true.

00:52:32.910 --> 00:52:37.870 position:56%
You're actually, as I said you're
scripting activity for humans to do.

00:52:37.870 --> 00:52:40.500
So you're not just writing an
abstract piece, you're writing,

00:52:40.500 --> 00:52:45.490 position:56%
you're choreographing something that
performers are going to want to,

00:52:45.490 --> 00:52:48.000 position:56%
are going to actually physically do.

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:53.050
So next time you see a percussion
ensemble, just watch the,

00:52:53.050 --> 00:52:57.860
there are two in particular; Eric
Chow Beach, that's soul percussion.

00:52:57.860 --> 00:53:01.200
He's a skinny little guy and
he looks like he's dancing

00:53:01.200 --> 00:53:03.910
as he plays the percussion
instruments.

00:53:06.050 --> 00:53:08.560
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: We have
time for one last question.

00:53:08.560 --> 00:53:11.020
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: I'll hold
my breath [laughter].

00:53:11.020 --> 00:53:13.890
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: Somebody
please, we have one over here.

00:53:21.050 --> 00:53:25.070
&gt;&gt; So I'm impressed that in the
audio file world people are going

00:53:25.070 --> 00:53:31.840
from transistors back to vacuum
tubes and you composed during

00:53:31.840 --> 00:53:35.580
that period of transition, I
would assume, where you started

00:53:35.580 --> 00:53:37.890
with the amplification
was more based

00:53:37.890 --> 00:53:40.630
on tubes moving into transistors.

00:53:40.630 --> 00:53:47.260
Did you sense a lack of warmth as
things became so fully digital?

00:53:47.260 --> 00:53:52.760
&gt;&gt; Paul Lansky: I sort
of think this whole back

00:53:52.760 --> 00:54:00.460
to vinyl is simple minded.

00:54:00.460 --> 00:54:05.150
My first experience with the
difference between digital

00:54:05.150 --> 00:54:08.190
and vinyl was with
my Campion Fantasies.

00:54:08.190 --> 00:54:12.020
I did the piece, I spent the year

00:54:12.020 --> 00:54:14.100
and a half doing it,
and it was great.

00:54:14.100 --> 00:54:18.130
I was very proud of it
and I got a recording.

00:54:18.130 --> 00:54:19.620
It was issued on an LP

00:54:19.620 --> 00:54:24.700
when I composing recording
and it was great.

00:54:24.700 --> 00:54:27.920
I played it, played
it once and at the end

00:54:27.920 --> 00:54:33.300
of the thing there's a loud
part and it sounded awful.

00:54:33.300 --> 00:54:34.680
It sounded nothing like that.

00:54:34.680 --> 00:54:36.660
I asked my father what was going on

00:54:36.660 --> 00:54:40.590
and he said just inter
diameter distortion.

00:54:40.590 --> 00:54:44.640
It's the angle of the
needle changes with,

00:54:44.640 --> 00:54:48.960 position:56%
as you get to the end of the record.

00:54:48.960 --> 00:54:50.860
And I noticed back in those days,

00:54:50.860 --> 00:54:55.010
you know I still had good high
frequency hearing and I'd listen

00:54:55.010 --> 00:54:59.180
to a recording once and it sounded
great and I'd listen to it twice

00:54:59.180 --> 00:55:02.590
and the second time
it sounded less good.

00:55:02.590 --> 00:55:05.310
Actually a young faculty
members at Princeton used to wait

00:55:05.310 --> 00:55:10.190
at the record library to get
recordings of pieces that were,

00:55:10.190 --> 00:55:13.970
that were, hadn't been played
so you can take them home

00:55:13.970 --> 00:55:16.880
and play them for the first time.

00:55:16.880 --> 00:55:22.030
So I was really not thrilled
with the analog world.

00:55:22.030 --> 00:55:24.520
Also the fact is that
if you made a copy

00:55:24.520 --> 00:55:27.380
of something you degrade the copy.

00:55:27.380 --> 00:55:30.470
So after recording something,

00:55:30.470 --> 00:55:33.490
you know recording something then
recording the recording of that

00:55:33.490 --> 00:55:35.430
and then recording
the recording of that,

00:55:35.430 --> 00:55:37.950
it gets more and more distorted.

00:55:37.950 --> 00:55:43.800
So I constantly was battling
with the, with the problems

00:55:43.800 --> 00:55:49.020
of analog recording and the thing
I love about digital recording is

00:55:49.020 --> 00:55:56.290 position:56%
that you can copy it an infinite
number of times and I think this is,

00:55:56.290 --> 00:55:58.010
you know a significant difference.

00:55:58.010 --> 00:56:02.460
So it is, that's not to say
that there's not some problem

00:56:02.460 --> 00:56:07.290
with digital recording, but I
think that anything that you can do

00:56:07.290 --> 00:56:09.050
in analog you can do in digital

00:56:09.050 --> 00:56:13.320
if you have a high
enough sampling rate.

00:56:13.320 --> 00:56:14.850
Does that make sense?

00:56:14.850 --> 00:56:16.150
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:56:16.150 --> 00:56:17.450
&gt;&gt; David Plylar: That's
a great answer.

00:56:17.450 --> 00:56:21.870
Well thank you, let's thank Paul
Lansky for speaking with us today

00:56:21.870 --> 00:56:24.160 position:56%
and I hope you all enjoy his pieces.

00:56:24.160 --> 00:56:25.960
I'm sure we all will.

00:56:25.960 --> 00:56:29.130
[ Applause ]

